Status scripts for GNOME Translation Project

README author: Stanislav Visnovsky <visnovsky@nenya.ms.mff.cuni.cz>


This file describes how to use the scripts for generating status HTML pages. It
describes my experience to get these scripts generate my local status page. I
hope it will help you to get them to work as well :-). Any comments are welcome.

You need to download a file describing which CVS modules should be used (called modules.dat).
It is in GNOME CVS module web-devel-2. In fact, there are three files; stable,
unstable and extra:

web-devel-2/content/projects/gtp/status/unstable/modules.dat
web-devel-2/content/projects/gtp/status/stable/modules.dat
web-devel-2/content/projects/gtp/status/extra/modules.dat

Get them typing:

cvs checkout web-devel-2/content/projects/gtp/status/unstable/modules.dat
cvs checkout web-devel-2/content/projects/gtp/status/stable/modules.dat
cvs checkout web-devel-2/content/projects/gtp/status/extra/modules.dat

There are 3 steps to generate the HTML statistics using modules.dat files:

1. cvs-download.pl
The script allows to checkout or update your local CVS tree according to 
a modules.dat file.

For example using unstable (please replace <your-GNOME-CVS-root> by the correct
path):
./cvs-download.pl --cvsroot-dir <your-GNOME-CVS-root> \
  --modules-file <your-GNOME-CVS-root>/web-devel-2/content/projects/gtp/status/unstable/modules.dat


2. status.pl
The script generates statistics for your local CVS tree, using modules.dat file
again:

Example using unstable again (please replace <your-GNOME-CVS-root> by the
correct path and <result-path> by the path, where you want to store generated
pages):
./status.pl --cvsroot-dir <your-GNOME-CVS-root> \
   --modules-file <your-GNOME-CVS-root>web-devel-2/content/projects/gtp/status/unstable/modules.dat \
   --html-dir <result-path>

3. genthml.pl
Finally, using this script, you generate the HTML pages with the statistics
(again replace <result-path> by the path used in the previous step for
--html-dir:

./genhtml.pl --html-dir <result-path>

In <result-path> you should get statistics pages named status.shtml and
<lang>.shtml.
To generate statistics for your language only, change the @langs in the
"Constants" part of the script status.pl before executing status.pl.

